@artwr Thanks. I force pushed this time around since setting up CI would have required at least one other force push as well. 

I will be setting up CI for future PRs.

Thanks for the review.

@tedmiston that's actually a good point. I've added the JS linting documentation in CONTRIBUTING.md file. 

Travis Build Result: https://travis-ci.org/verdan/incubator-airflow/builds/408402612

Followup Jira issue: https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/AIRFLOW-2803 (To fix all the linting issues)

Here's a WIP start to the follow up discussion from https://github.com/apache/incubator-airflow/pull/3642.  I'm starting the longer term solution by seeing if upgrading the relevant dependencies makes a difference.

@Fokko Do you have any advice around how to test this intermittent error on CI?  Basically I'd like to trigger the build ~5–10x times in a row on some combinations of [MySQL, PostgreSQL] x [Python subversions] and see how many (if any) succeed vs error out.

Note: I have an open task to get Travis CI setup on my GitHub account.  I understand Airflow is using significant resources for Apache on Travis, so getting that setup is a priority.

@XD-DENG Can you prepend the squash the commits and prepend the message with the Jira ticket `[AIRFLOW-2809] ...`

This looks like a good idea to me, maybe check what the other committers think about this.

cc @kaxil @bolkedebruin @jgao54

@cctvzd7 ty for your idea. Persisting DAG is a much bigger problem and would need a more complicated solution( there're a few challenges there e.g. serialize task dependency graph). It would be nice feature tho, since it would enable useful stuff like DAG versioning.

Note that we will still need to parse the DAG file even it has not changed since we cannot share DAG objects across processes, since not all DAGs are pickable which is the root problem. And there should be no need to actually parse DAG if we have centralized DAG parsing/storage. Finally we will still need a major surgery for `models.py` since it is vastly using the actual DAG and task objects.

Cheers.
